close_symbols: OS_FdSet (type/struct definition, including object_ids element type and array length)
explanation:
Why each symbol is required:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro/implementation): This macro appears at the start of the function and can change control flow (e.g. log, abort, or return on a NULL pointer). Its exact behaviour determines whether the subsequent code can execute or whether side effects (logging/abort) occur — necessary to decide if code is actually reachable/executed and if removal would change behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex (function and implementation): The conditional body is guarded by the return value of this function. To know whether the bit-clear operation can ever execute (and under what conditions), and whether the function has other observable side effects, its implementation and return-value semantics (when it returns OS_SUCCESS) are required.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM (constant): Passed into OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex; the meaning of this constant affects how ObjectIdToArrayIndex validates objid and therefore whether OS_SUCCESS can be returned for certain objid values.

- OS_SUCCESS (return-code constant): The if-condition compares return_code to OS_SUCCESS; the exact numeric value and semantics are needed to interpret the conditional and to relate to possible return values of OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex.

- OS_FdSet (type/struct definition, including object_ids element type and array length): The statement that may be dead modifies Set->object_ids[local_id >> 3]. To determine whether this write has any observable effect (i.e., is dead), you must know the element type (e.g., uint8_t vs wider), the array bounds/size (to rule out UB or out-of-bounds writes), and how/where object_ids is used elsewhere.

- osal_index_t (typedef): The type of local_id influences value range and therefore which bit and array index are affected; needed to reason about possible indices and whether the mask can change state.

- osal_id_t (typedef): The type of objid influences the domain of inputs to OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex and thus whether OS_SUCCESS and different local_id values are possible.

- OS_printf (function): Appears in the static call graph and may be invoked by OS_CHECK_POINTER or OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex for reporting. Its presence/behaviour (e.g., side effects on I/O) is relevant to whether removing logging/printing in error paths would change observable behaviour.

Note: To fully determine whether the bit-clear is dead in the global program sense (i.e., removal would not affect behaviour), one would also need to inspect all code that reads/relies on OS_FdSet.object_ids (callers/consumers of the FD set). Those are not listed here because they constitute a wider program analysis, but the OS_FdSet definition is included to enable that follow-up analysis.
